  :prose
"A number by itself lies. '5' could be 5 meters, 5 seconds, 5 kilograms,
5 dollars, or 5 anythings. In physics simulation this ambiguity is
where most bugs live. You multiply a mass by a velocity thinking
you're getting momentum, but you actually multiplied by a distance
and got momentum-times-time — off by a factor. The sim behaves
weirdly and you don't know why.

Dimensional analysis is the technique of tagging numbers with their
units and letting the computer check that operations are consistent.
Motoi Scheme's `phys/quantity` and family do this. This appendix
walks through ten worked bugs — real errors dimensional analysis
would have caught before you ran the sim.

---

## B.1 phys/quantity and friends

```scheme
(define distance (phys/quantity 5 :unit 'meter))
(define time     (phys/quantity 2 :unit 'second))
(define velocity (phys/q/ distance time))
(phys/dimension velocity)
;; => (:length 1 :time -1)      -> meters per second, correct

(phys/same-dimension? velocity (phys/quantity 3 :unit 'm/s))
;; => #t
```

`phys/q+`, `phys/q-`, `phys/q*`, `phys/q/` all propagate units and
check compatibility. Adding meters to seconds is an error caught
before evaluation.

```scheme
(phys/q+ distance time)
;; => ERROR: incompatible dimensions (:length 1) and (:time 1)
```

## B.2 Ten worked bugs

### Bug 1: The 3600 factor.

```scheme
;; WRONG:
(define speed 60)                       ;; kilometers per hour
(define distance-covered (* speed 30))  ;; 30 seconds later
;; => 1800 ??? "the car went 1800 kilometers in 30 seconds"

;; RIGHT:
(define speed (phys/quantity 60 :unit 'km/hr))
(define time  (phys/quantity 30 :unit 'second))
(define distance-covered (phys/q* speed time))
;; => 0.5 km    (correct!)
```

The units force the conversion: 60 km/hr * 30 s = 60/3600 km/s * 30 s
= 0.5 km. Without units the '60' was interpreted as km/frame or
whatever your sim used, and the answer was wildly wrong.

### Bug 2: Radians vs degrees.

```scheme
;; WRONG:
(sin 30)   ;; the sine of 30 RADIANS = -0.988
;; when you meant the sine of 30 DEGREES = 0.5

;; RIGHT:
(sin (phys/degrees->radians 30))
;; => 0.5
```

The `sin` function takes radians. Passing degrees gives absurd
answers.

### Bug 3: Mass vs weight.

```scheme
;; WRONG:
(entity/mass! b 150)   ;; setting weight of 150 pounds as mass
;; -> the sim treats a person as 150 kg (mass), not 150 lbs (weight)

;; RIGHT:
(define weight (phys/quantity 150 :unit 'lb-force))
(define mass   (phys/q/ weight (phys/quantity 9.81 :unit 'm/s^2)))
(entity/mass! b (phys/value-in-unit mass 'kg))
;; => ~68 kg  (correct!)
```

Weight is a force; mass is a mass. Conflating them is a factor-of-g
error, which for Earth is about 10.

### Bug 4: Energy vs power.

```scheme
;; WRONG:
(define bulb-consumption 60)                ;; watts
(define hours-on         8)
(define bill              (* bulb-consumption hours-on))
;; => 480 ... watts? watt-hours? kilowatt-hours?

;; RIGHT:
(define bulb (phys/quantity 60 :unit 'watt))
(define time (phys/quantity 8 :unit 'hour))
(define usage (phys/q* bulb time))
(phys/value-in-unit usage 'kwh)
;; => 0.48 kilowatt-hours
```

Watts are joules per second. Watt-hours are joules. Kilowatt-hours
are 3.6 million joules. Bills are in kilowatt-hours. Confusing them
costs money.

### Bug 5: Spring constant units.

```scheme
;; k = 100 N/m in physics land. If your sim uses pixels for length
;; and 1/60-second for time, 1 sim-second = 60 sim-frames, and
;; k needs to be rescaled.

;; WRONG:
(world/link-stiffness! spring 100)     ;; treated as sim-units, absurdly stiff

;; RIGHT: pre-convert.
(define k-physical (phys/quantity 100 :unit 'N/m))
(define scale     (phys/quantity 100 :unit 'px/m))  ;; 100 pixels per meter
(define k-sim     (phys/value-in-sim-units k-physical scale))
(world/link-stiffness! spring k-sim)
```

Whenever your sim uses non-SI units (pixels, frames), you need a
consistent conversion. Do it once at the boundary, not scattered
through your code.

### Bug 6: Angular velocity.

```scheme
;; WRONG:
(entity/angular-vel! b 360)     ;; 360 ... degrees per second? rotations?
;; -> 360 rad/s is very fast; 360 deg/s is one revolution/s

;; RIGHT:
(entity/angular-vel! b (phys/quantity 360 :unit 'deg/s))
```

### Bug 7: Gravitational constant.

```scheme
;; The gravitational constant G = 6.674e-11 N*m^2/kg^2 (SI).
;; But your sim uses pixels for length, sim-frames for time...
;; The 'G' you pass to world/attract! is EFFECTIVE G in sim units.

;; If you want realistic orbits at solar-system scale, you need to
;; work out the conversion:
;;    G_sim = G * (pixels/meter)^-3 * (frames/second)^2 * kg-scale
;; A mess. Better: use realistic physical units end-to-end (Appendix I).
```

### Bug 8: Torque vs energy.

```scheme
;; Both have units of N*m. But they are NOT the same physical quantity.
;; Torque is a rotational force. Energy is joules.
;; Motoi's phys/dimension will report the same for both, so you must
;; label at the semantic level:
(define torque (phys/quantity 5 :unit 'Nm-torque))
(define energy (phys/quantity 5 :unit 'joule))
;; The unit system treats them as compatible dimensionally but the
;; :unit tag preserves the semantic distinction.
```

### Bug 9: Off by 2*pi in Fourier.

```scheme
;; When you compute a frequency f = omega / (2 pi), and you drop
;; the 2 pi, your natural frequency is off by 6.28. If you tune
;; a resonance chart, you're at the wrong pole.

;; RIGHT: label explicitly.
(define omega (phys/quantity 6.28 :unit 'rad/s))
(define f     (phys/q/ omega (phys/quantity (* 2 3.14159) :unit 'rad/cycle)))
(phys/value-in-unit f 'hz)   ;; => 1
```

### Bug 10: Newtons in a screen-pixel-per-frame world.

```scheme
;; You want a force of 10 N applied to a 1 kg mass at 60 fps.
;; a = F/m = 10 m/s^2.
;; In sim frames: a = 10 (m/s^2) / (60 frames/s)^2 * (100 px/m)
;;              = 10 / 3600 * 100 = 0.278 px/frame^2

;; WRONG:
(world/impulse! b 10 0)   ;; treated as 10 px/frame velocity impulse. WAY too much.

;; RIGHT:
(define F (phys/quantity 10 :unit 'N))
(define m (phys/quantity  1 :unit 'kg))
(define dt (phys/quantity 1 :unit 'frame))
(define impulse (phys/q* F dt))
(entity/apply-impulse! b (phys/value-in-sim impulse))
```

---

## B.3 A checked pipeline

Set units at the boundaries; let the middle be dimensionless. Or
carry units through everywhere. Both are fine; MIXING them is
dangerous.

Alfred's discipline: at the top of every simulation file, declare
your unit system.

```scheme
;;; Units: length = pixel; time = frame (60 fps); mass = kg;
;;;        force = kg*px/frame^2; energy = kg*px^2/frame^2
;;; Conversions: 100 px = 1 m; 60 frames = 1 s.
```

Every entering quantity gets converted at the entry point:

```scheme
(define (m->px m) (* m 100))
(define (s->frame s) (* s 60))
```

Every exiting quantity gets converted at the exit point:

```scheme
(define (px->m p) (/ p 100))
(define (frame->s f) (/ f 60))
```

Inside the sim, everything is in the sim's native units. This is
what Motoi Scheme uses internally, and it makes the sim code shorter
and faster while keeping the boundary conversions honest.

---

## B.4 The takeaway

Half the physics bugs in games are unit-mismatch bugs, and the
programmer never sees the mismatch — the sim just behaves oddly.
`phys/dimension` and `phys/same-dimension?` catch these BEFORE you
run. Ten seconds of dimensional check saves an hour of 'why does my
pendulum swing so fast.'

Related:
- Chapter 1: raw sim units, no dimensional checking
- Chapter 11: uncertainty propagation through RLC formulas
- Appendix I: SI units for solar-system-scale physics")
